":"1558","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1454":"1454","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","Northowram, Yorkshire, England":"Northowram, Yorkshire, England","Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":1,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":95,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":104,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret was born in 1454, in Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England. She had at least 1 son with Jeffery Mawde."},"et":{"1454–":"1454–Surnud","1457–1540":"1457–1540","1477–1532":"1477–1532","1454–Female":"1454–Surnud","1558":"1558","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1454":"1454","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","Northowram, Yorkshire, England":"Northowram, Yorkshire, England","Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1454–":"1454–Kuollut","1457–1540":"1457–1540","1477–1532":"1477–1532","1454–Female":"1454–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1454":"1454","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","Northowram, Yorkshire, England":"Northowram, Yorkshire, England","Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1454–":"1454–Décédée","1457–1540":"1457–1540","1477–1532":"1477–1532","1454–Female":"1454–Décédée","1558":"1558","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1454":"1454","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","Northowram, Yorkshire, England":"Northowram, Everwyck, Angleterre","Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret est née en 1454, à Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Jeffery Mawde."},"de":{"1454–":"1454–Verstorben","1457–1540":"1457–1540","1477–1532":"1477–1532","1454–Female":"1454–Verstorben","1558":"1558","1457":"1457","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1532":"1532","1454":"1454","1540":"1540","1549":"1549","Northowram, Yorkshire, England":"Northowram, Yorkshire, England","Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England":"Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England","lifeSummary":"Margaret wurde 1454 in Ilketshall St Andrew, Suffolk, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Jeffery Mawde mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1454–":"1454–Desede","14